  "prompt": "Are there legal obligations for financial institutions regarding money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, financial institutions have significant legal obligations to prevent money laundering. These typically include:\n\n1. Customer Due Diligence (CDD)\n- Verifying customer identities\n- Monitoring transactions\n- Reporting suspicious activities\n\n2. Reporting Requirements\n- Filing Suspicious Activity Reports (SARs)\n- Reporting large cash transactions\n- Maintaining transaction records\n\n3. Anti-Money Laundering (AML) Compliance Programs\n- Developing internal policies\n- Conducting staff training\n- Implementing screening procedures\n\n4. Know Your Customer (KYC) Regulations\n- Gathering detailed customer information\n- Assessing customer risk profiles\n- Conducting background checks\n\n5. International Compliance\n- Following global standards like FATF recommendations\n- Adhering to international anti-money laundering regulations\n\n6. Potential Penalties\n- Significant financial fines\n- Potential criminal liability\n- Loss of banking licenses\n\nThese obligations are designed to prevent financial crimes and help law enforcement track potential illegal activities.",
